      "id": "037fd705f5ed94e5",
      "text": ">Indigenous Ways of Knowing (IWOK), also referred to as Indigenous worldview, is an epistemological way of knowing and being based in interconnectedness. Indigenous knowledge comes from a community being in an interrelated relationship with the land in a particular location on Earth over many generations and continuously passing that knowledge on to future generations. While it is widely recognized that there is not a single universal Indigenous belief system, since Indigenous peoples throughout the world vary widely in terms of geography, language, and social structure, it is accepted by prominent scholars that there are many key similarities among Indigenous philosophical approaches that together form the foundation of IWOK. \n>\n[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indigenous_Ways_of_Knowing wikipedia]"
